nt-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> through targeted action alongside </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">inclusion in mainstream programmes, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">it will impact achievement of all international development targets</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. DFID should therefore consider targeted action</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to increase its engagement in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">disa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">bility focused </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">development</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">at all levels.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Data on disability is weak in many developing countries. Up to date, accurate data underpins effective development delivery. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> If DFID is able to contribute to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> or influence</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the development of stronger data it woul</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d make a significant impact in terms of understanding need better and therefore delivering more impactful progammes.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Disability was omitted from the Millennium Development Goals. DFID should advocate for the inclusion of disability in the post 2015 develop</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ment goals.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Active engagement of disabled people and their families adds value to any disability work. It empowers disabled people and sends out a strong message that they are valuable, active citizens. DFID should engage with disabled people in any strate</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">gic, policy or delivery development</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and implementation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Their voice is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> important.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">International Service</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">International Service is a development organisation that has been changing lives for the better for more than 60 years by empowering some of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">world’s poorest and most marginalised people.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Our international programmes are in West Africa, Latin America and the occupied Palestinian territory where social and economic inclusion for all people is central to our work.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">International Service’s developme</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nt</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">workers support local project partners</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">with specialist skills and knowledge so</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">that they and their organisations grow</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in effectiveness and impact.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Our work is also about influencing the development and delivery</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of human rights policies in the countries </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">where we operate on</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">behalf of vulnerable and excluded groups of people.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">International Service is currently part of the consortium of agencies delivering the International Citizenship</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Service (ICS) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">funded through DFID.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Our inclusion programme has a focus on</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> disability and we also work with disability projects as part of our work within the ICS programme. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Further information on International Service and our work can be found at </span><a href="http://www.internationalservice.org.uk"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">www.internationalservice.org.</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">uk</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Reasons for submission</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We are submitting evidence to this enquiry as we firmly believe that disability is still marginalised in international development. The omission of disability in the Millennium Development Goals </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">led to disability being left ou</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t of many development programmes.  A targeted approach is needed to redress the existing imbalance and the influence and action of DFID is vital in taking forward this agenda.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Identified issues and proposed responses</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Over 15% of the world</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s population </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">have a disability. Disability is closely linked to poverty</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and in developing countries this group is known to be one of the most marginalised and vulnerable in society.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It is commonly accepted that disabled people have lower employment rates and lower edu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cational attainment (WHO) – and in developing countries access to employment and education is significantly reduced</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> or non </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">existent</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  There is also a financial loss for governments through lost productivity, and lost taxes through non or low employment of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> disabled people, alongside high health and social care costs. So inclusion makes sense economically and in terms of reducing poverty – a central aim of DFID policy.</span><a name="_GoBack"></a></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Disability has been </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">further </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">marginalised through its omission from the Millennium Developm</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ent Goals (MDGs)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> as a result is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> frequently side-lined within mainstream development work. DFID has a clear role to play in influencing the formation of whatever replaces the MDGs in 2015 and ensuring that disability is firmly placed within the new fram</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ework.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The United Nations Convention on the Rights of People with Disabilities (CRPD)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> should underpin any disability development work – specifically the implementation of articles 4,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">9,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">24,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">27 and 29</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> – awareness raising, accessibility, education, work and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">employment, and participation in political and public life</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> The CRDP </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">provides a clear international framework which 158 out of 193 UN member states have signed up to. Therefore, the CRPD provides a strong </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and commonly accepted </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">platform on which to build </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">future development wor</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">k and measure achievement and impact.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The UK has in the past been a leader in disability development and in promoting inclusion and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">social model of disability. We still have much to share with other countries</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and specifically with</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> NGOs and communities in developing cou</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ntries through empowerment, cap</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">acity building and advocacy. The development of a separate disability strategy by DFID </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">would reinforce their commitment to the issue following </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the recent announcement that all</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> new DFID-f</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">unded schools will be made accessible to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">disabled children. A focused strategy would demonstrate that DFID give equal importance to disability as they do to other development areas and recognise the need to address some of the unique challenges across the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">disability sector in international development. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Disability should still remain part of DFIDs sector programmes, for example in education, health</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, livelihoods</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">etc., </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> but a stand-alone disability strategy and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">programme of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">focused development work would rais</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e the profile and importance </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of this work and make a greater, more sustainable </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">impact.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Active engagement of disabled people – including children and young adults is vital in developing any strategy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n any development work overseas including in the plan</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ning, management and monitoring of DFID programmes.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> This could be facilitated by development organisations already working with disabled peoples</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> organisations</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> both in the UK and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in developing countries.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Data and statistics on disability are weak, and ofte</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n inaccurate or incomplete in most developing countries</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> making it difficult to benchmark activity against need. Any influence or contribution DFID could make to strengthen this area would be valuable in enabling accurate identification and meeting of need</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Conclusion</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Investment in d</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">isability</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> with</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">international </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">development remains marginalised. It is important that DFID sets a strong example in promoting the need to address disability not just as part of its sector </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">programmes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> but in its own right. A stra</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tegic framework developed with the full engagement of disabled people</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and working alongside international development agencies with a disability focus would be the first step to achieving this. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Investment in supporting research, data collection, capacity </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">building and advocacy would underpin the development of services and opportunities for disabled people in developing countries</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> empowering and equipping them to make a valid, economically and socially productive, contribution to society.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>